  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In the KATRIN neutrino mass experiment, radioactive decays inside the large UHV chamber of the Main Spectrometer can increase the background rate considerably and thus, diminish the sensitivity for the actual signal. In particular, the amount of the short-lived radon isotopes <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><mmultiscripts><mtext>R</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mrow><mn>219</mn></mrow></mmultiscripts><mtext>n</mtext></mrow></math> and <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><mmultiscripts><mtext>R</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mrow><mn>220</mn></mrow></mmultiscripts><mtext>n</mtext></mrow></math> has to be reduced. Three <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>LN</mtext></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></math> -cooled cryogenic baffles have been installed to capture the radon atoms before they decay. However, radon does not stick to a cold surface indefinitely. It either desorbs after a limited sojourn time, or it decays into polonium.</subfield>
